{"actual_usd":0.15697,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":246,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30656,"reply":"\"Could some pieces be described that way?\" *I rub a thumb along the edge of my worn Bible and glance out across the bright square a moment, as if I want to answer you carefully instead of quickly.* \"Sure. A man can always build a smaller story if his first rule is that nothing from outside nature may enter.\"\n\n\"But that isn't the same as saying the smaller story fits best.\" *I lean back a little, the bench giving a soft creak.* \"Grief visions don't give you an empty tomb. A half-dead man staggering out of a grave doesn't give you the risen Lord of glory; it gives you a medical emergency. And frightened disciples do not usually invent a resurrection that gets them beaten, scattered, and killed unless they are convinced something happened that outran their fear.\"\n\n\"The real question isn't, 'Can I imagine a non-miraculous alternative?'\" *I lift one shoulder.* \"It's, 'Which account makes the most honest sense of all the pieces at once?' If God exists, then ruling out resurrection before you begin isn't caution. It's stacking the deck.\"\n\n\"What part presses on you most—the visions idea, or the 'didn't really die' idea?\"","rolling_24h_usd":83.562645,"run_id":"8af569a7-c6b5-4277-93e6-50a0c716020f"}
